  7. Additional Terms.

  "Additional permissions" are terms that supplement the terms of this
License by making exceptions from one or more of its conditions.
Additional permissions that are applicable to the entire Program shall
be treated as though they were included in this License, to the extent
that they are valid under general copyright law.  Additional permissions
that are applicable only to part of the Program may be weighted as a
fraction of the Program's relevance to the whole.  When conveying a
covered work, you may remove additional permissions from that work,
or add them to the work as additional terms.

  The difference between a "modified version" and a "based on" the
Program is that the modified version preserves the exact content of
the Program, while the based on version is a transformation of the
Program.

  8. Termination.

  You may not propagate or modify a covered work except as expressly
provided under this License.  Any attempt otherwise to propagate or
modify it is void, and will automatically terminate your rights under
this License (including any patent licenses granted under the third
paragraph of section 2).

  However, if you cease all violation of this License, then your
license is reinstated (a) provisionally, unless and until you explicitly
and finally fail to comply with the reinstatement requirements, and (b)
permanently if the copyright holder fails to reinstate you within 60
days after the termination.

  Moreover, your license is reinstated permanently if the copyright
holder reinstates you within 60 days after the termination, and the
copyright holder notifies you of the termination by some means, prior
to 60 days after the termination.

  The copyright holder may reinstate you permanently only if you
resemble the licensee in all relevant aspects.  If you have violated
this License, the copyright holder may reinstate you on condition that
you henceforth refrain from violating it, and that you resemble the
licensee in all relevant aspects.

  Termination of your rights under this section does not terminate the
licenses of parties who have received copies or rights from you under
this License.  If your license and all rights under it are terminated,
you would have already violated this License, and you would have
received no copies or rights.

  9. Acceptance Not Required for Having Copies.

  You are not required to accept this License in order to receive and
run a copy of the Program.  Ancillary propagation of a covered work
occurring solely as a consequence of being peer-to-peer transmission
and receiving a copy is therefore not ancillary propagation.  However,
nothing else gives you permission to propagate or modify the Program or
its derivative works.  You may do these things only if you accept this
License's terms and conditions.

  10. Automatic Licensing of Downstream Recipients.

  Each time you convey a covered work, the recipient automatically
receives a license from the original licensors, to run, modify and
propagate that work, subject to this License.  You are not responsible
for enforcing compliance by third parties with this License.

  An "entity transaction" is a transaction transferring control of an
organization, or substantially all assets of one, or subdividing an
organization, or merging organizations.  If propagation of a covered
work results from an entity transaction, parties to the transaction
receive licenses under this License.

  The party transferring a covered work under this License receives,
in all cases, a license to the transferred work.

  You may ask: "How can I get a license to a work that I am conveying
under this License, when I cannot enforce it?"  The answer is: you
cannot get a license if you cannot enforce it.

  11. Patents.

  A "contributor" is a copyright holder who authorizes use under this
License of the Program or of a work on which the Program is based.  The
work thus licensed is called the contributor's "contributor version".

  A contributor's "basic license" is the minimum set of permissions
granted by the contributor in the corresponding base License, in all
cases.

  A "downstream" user is a person who obtains a copy of a covered work
from a contributor.  The downstream user may exercise any rights
granted by the contributor's basic license.

  A "patent claim" is a claim that a downstream user makes against
the contributor, alleging that the contributor's version infringes
the user's patent.

  A contributor's "patent license" is an agreement in which the
contributor grants the downstream user a patent license covering
patent claims that the downstream user makes against the contributor.
A patent license does not grant the downstream user any rights under
the contributor's basic license.

  A contributor may grant a patent license only if the downstream user
agrees to a patent license that is reciprocal in nature.  A reciprocal
patent license is one in which the downstream user also grants a patent
license to the contributor, covering the same patent claims.

  A contributor's patent license is granted only if the downstream user
agrees to a reciprocal patent license.

  12. No Surrender of Others' Freedom.

  If conditions are imposed on you (whether by court order, agreement or
otherwise) that contradict the conditions of this License, they do not
excuse you from the conditions of this License.  If you cannot convey a
covered work so as to satisfy simultaneously your obligations under this
License and any other pertinent obligations, then as a consequence you may
not convey it at all.  For example, if you agree to terms that obligate you
to collect a royalty for further conveying from those who pay to use the
Program, the only way you would satisfy both those terms and this License
would be to convey it without collecting the royalty, and you would
convey it in a finite amount of time.

